did.abstract: Collection include books, correspondence, articles, scrapbooks, notes, travelogues and a cap and gown of David S. Brown, who was Professor Emeritus of Management in the School of Government and business administration and program director for 31 years. The materials range in date from 1915-89.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: David Springer Brown (1915-96) was a Professor Emeritus of Management in the School of Government and business administration at The George Washington University, where he was a faculty member and program director for 31 years. Dr. Brown was among those principally responsible for the creation of the Department of Public Administration at the university, functioning as coordinator, director, and chair. This included creating a masters degree program in association management, the first such in the country.

Dr. Brown was born in Maine in 1915, and earned his A.B. from the University of Maine and Ph.D. from Syracuse University. He served as a bomber pilot for the U.S. Navy in World War II, and saved his own life by jumping from a burning plane at 500 feet. His passion for flying continued throughout his life; he piloted 15 or 20 different kinds of aircraft. Prior to his coming to The George Washington University, Professor Brown served several private companies and also four federal agencies including the Department of Agriculture, the Civil Aeronautics Administration, the Air Coordinating Committee, and the Marshall Plan. In 1953, As executive secretary of the Mutual Secretary Program's Public Advisory Board, he helped inaugurate and undertake the first presidential level study of American Trade and Tariff Policy in American history.

He joined the faculty of GW in 1954 and specialized in the management of large organizations and bureaucracy. He was the author of several books, including Management Concepts and Practices, Management's Hidden Enemy - and What Can Be Done About It, Managing the Large Organization, and Federal Contributions to Management. In addition, he wrote several monographs and over 200 professional articles and book reviews. While at GW, he directed a number of programs. These included a senior executive program for the Veterans Administration, the Air Force Advanced Management Program, and a master's degree program in the management of national resources at the Industrial College of the Armed forces.

Dr. Brown appeared professionally as a speaker or trainer in a majority of the states and in several foreign countries. In 1958, he was Visiting American Professor at Chesters, a management training center in Glasgow, Scotland. He lectured for the U.S. Information Agency in Europe and Africa, directed many management training programs for both public and private sectors, and served as a management consultant. For several years he was President and later Chairman of the Board of Leadership Resources, Inc., a management training company.
Dr. Brown retired from GW in 1986, and died March 11, 1996.

An oral history done with Dr. Brown in 1989 can be found in MS0371, the Oral History Collection. The History Museum in Gelman Library was renamed the David S. Brown Memorabilia Room in November 2003 following a donation to the Library by his widow, Anne Elizon Brown. The collection was donated to the University Archives in three accessions by David S. Brown and Anne Elizon Brown in 1986, 1994, and 1997.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include books, correspondence, articles, scrapbooks, notes, travelogues and a cap and gown. They range in date from 1915-89, and were donated to the University Archives in four accessions by David S. Brown and Anne Elizon Brown in 1986, 1994, and 1997.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into 11 series: Books; Papers; Additional writings; Correspondence; Training materials used in classes; Faculty articles; Miscellaneous articles and manuscripts; Memorabilia; Personal papers; Professional writings; Scrapbooks.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains scrapbooks of clippings, photographs, letters, and memorabilia primarily documenting David S. Brown's family life from his birth in 1915 through 1985.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A green scrapbook (15" x 12" x 2.5") containing records of David S. Brown's life from birth through a graduation from the University of Maine. Family trees, photographs of relatives and childhood photographs are included. From Brown's high school and college years are letters, papers written for classes, oratorical awards, early bylines and certificates of graduation and promotion. Of historical significance are a 1927 photograph of Charles E. Lindbergh on a postcard, newspaper clippings on the subject of the New Deal, and a personal letter to Brown from Maine Congressman Brewster.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A brown scrapbook (14.5" x 12.25" x 1.5") containing photographs, newspaper clippings and letters to family members from Brown during his days as a student and teacher at Syracuse University and as a Navy pilot. A certificate is included which establishes Brown as a "Challenger" for the Democratic Party in the 1936 New York State elections. Of historical interest is the front page section of The Corpus Christi Caller - Times from January 17, 1943 with the lead story; "140,000 Nazis Slaughtered at Stalingrad: U.S. Planes Shoot Down 30 Jap Planes, Blast Four Ships".

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A maroon scrapbook (12" x 9" x 2.5") containing photographs, newspaper clippings, letters and telegrams to Brown from Evelyn Lovett and to Lovett from Brown chronicling the couple's courtship and marriage. Several volumes of a satirical paper written by Brown while in the Navy are included. The Weekly Constitution (later called The Weekly Constitutional) includes volume I numbers 1-7 and volume III numbers 1 5. The birth of the Brown's first child, David Springer Brown, Jr. on March 7, 1944 is also recorded through announcements.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A green scrapbook (11.75" x 9.5" x 1.75") chronicling, through photographs, the Brown's wedding and first year of marriage. Of historical interest are an unused war ration book, a pamphlet illustrating U.S. Army, Navy and Marine Corps insignia and medals and an 8" x 10" black and white photograph of Mrs. Brown's father, Robert A. Lovette who was then the Secretary of War For Air. Also included is the cover of the May 1944 edition of Wings magazine featuring Lovett.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This red scrapbook (11.25" x 9.25" x 0.25") contains newspaper clippings from the Navy Air Services (NAS) Skywriter of a column written by Brown while in the Navy. The column, "Have You Heard", collected quotations by various Navy personnel in a humorous format. Noteworthy are articles from Skywriter that detail various downings, crashes or disappearances of Navy pilots. Airmen mentioned include, Captain Donald E. McCafferty and Lieutenant (jg) John W. Sebek. Also from Skywriter are articles detailing the promotion of Lieutenant Commander Frank A. Patriarca and Lieutenant Commander Raymond P. Kline.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This cream-colored scrapbook (11.25" x 8.25" x 0.5") was originally part of scrapbook number 5 and contains more articles from NAS Miami Skywriter written by Brown as well as his column "Have You Heard". Of special interest is a United States Navy Naval Aviator certificate from 1943.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A green, brown, cream and red woven cover scrapbook (15" X 12.75" x 1") containing newspaper clippings from the Bangor Daily News of Brown's column "Maine Live from Washington" detailing news from Washington, D.C. pertaining to Maine. Of historical interest is a page from the Congressional Record Appendix (p. 19097) with the text of two speeches "How to Murder a Democracy" given by the Honorable Gerald P. Nye of North Dakota, and "Public Opinion Polls and the Maine Election" given by the Honorable Walter M. Pierce of Oregon, both in September 1940. The later is particularly important as it deals with the implications of the use of the Gallup Opinion Polls to predict outcomes of elections. Also included in this scrapbook is the text of a speech delivered by Brown at Stephens College in Columbia, Missouri during a conference on "Women in Aviation" in May 1946. Brown chronicles the life of Mrs. Phoebe Fairgrave Omlie, a pioneer among women aviators.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: The cover of this blue scrapbook (12" x 10" x 2") has a picture of the shoulder patch for the VB-89 squadron, to which Brown belonged. In addition to letters, articles and photos chronicling the Browns' family life during this period. The scrapbook contains a significant amount of historical material. Among the artifacts are the actual patch from the VB-89 worn in World War II by Brown, a Civilian Army Pass, a Selective Service Registration Certificate from October 16, 1940, a war ration book, a newspaper photo (unknown source) of General McArthur at the Japanese surrender after WWII, Japanese money issued during the American occupation, and pictures taken in Japan during the occupation. Also included are a certificate from the Office of Scientific Research and Development issued March 1, 1945 commending Ms. Brown's contribution to WWII, and a "Plank Owner's Certificate" from the USS Antietam issued to Brown January 28, 1945 as a member of the ship's original crew. An issue of the USS Antietam Go-Get-'Am-Gazette (July 1945, Vol. I, No. 5) is also included. Another significant item is a rectangular piece of cloth printed with the American flag and a statement in French and oriental languages that begins "I am an American aviator. My plane was destroyed." The career of Robert A. Lovett is also chronicled in this scrapbook. Included are a September 18, 1945 New York Times article, "Stimson Resigns as War Secretary - Patterson Named" in which it is mentioned that Lovett resigns as Assistant Secretary of War for Air as well as various unidentified newspaper clippings detailing Dean Acheson's resignation and Lovett's appointment as Under Secretary of State under President Truman. An 8 x 10 photograph pictures Under Secretary Robert Patterson, Assistant Secretary John J. McCloy, Secretary Stimson, Assistant Secretary of Air Lovett and Special Assistant Harvey Bundy. In addition, two reproductions of documents are included, one of a letter signed by President Truman citing Lovett for Distinguished Service medal and one of the certificate awarding Lovett the medal on September 13, 1945, signed by Stimson and the Major General at the time.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This is a brown scrapbook (9.50" x 11.75" x 2"). In addition to numerous family photos, cards and telegrams, the birth certificate of the Brown's second son Christopher Lovett Brown born October 30, 1948 at Columbia Hospital Washington, D.C. Also contained in the book are numerous photographs of Washington D.C. landmarks such as Kenmore in Fredericksburg, Virginia, the home of George Washington's sister, Betty Lewis, Woodlawn, Home of Nellie Curtis Lewis, stepdaughter of George Washington, and Oak Hill near Oatlands, Virginia, home of James Monroe designed by Thomas Jefferson. Aerial photographs taken from Brown's plane include the housing development of Park Fairfax in Alexandria, Virginia, Mount Vernon, the Washington D.C. monument area, Bailey's Cross-roads Airport, the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier and Arlington Cemetery. An article on Park Fairfax from The Star is also included. Finally, a photograph of the landscaping plans for the new State Department by landscaper Hagermann is also included. Of significance are numerous newspaper clippings and newspaper photographs as well as actual photographs of Robert A. Lovett, George C. Marshall, Ambassador Rober D. Murphy and President Harry S. Truman in various meetings on foreign aid and policy testifying before the Senate on the Marshall Plan. A page from Time magazine, March 29, 1948, entitled "National Affairs" details America's international affairs after WWII. The 1949 presidential inauguration of Harry S. Truman is chronicled through many newspaper photographs of the ceremonies and parade. Also included is an invitation to the ceremonies, a seating plan of the President's platform, ceremonial and parade programs as well as an identifying "Inaugural Committee" medallion. A newspaper photograph with caption pictures the inaugural protest of some D.C. residents lobbying for votes in the presidential election. Miscellaneous historical events are included such as a newspaper photograph of Princess Ashraf, sister to the then Shah of Iran during her visit to Washington, D.C., an article dated November 1947 on the appointment of Dr. Samuel D. Marble at age 31 to the presidency of Wilmington College, making him the youngest college president at the time and a photograph of an early TV broadcast. Also included are a program from the National Symphony Orchestra Benefit performance for the opening of the Playhouse Theatre, April 27, 1948, obituaries of G. F. Scherer, Embassy aid in Mexico city and W. A. Jump, Director of Finance at USDA, and Ruth Flumo political cartoons. Finally the front section of the New York Times, January 22, 1946, is included with the headline story "President's Message On The State of the Union and Transmitting the Budget."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A brown scrapbook (9.25" x 11.75" x 1.50") that, in addition to family photos and Christmas cards, contains material from the June 7, 1949 meeting of the 3rd Assembly of the International Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal, Canada. Brown"s invitation to the event, a certificate from the US State Department naming Brown an advisor to the Assembly, and a photograph of the Assembly are included. The book also contains Brown's invitation to a National Air Council meeting in Washington, D.C. on the topic "Economic Consequences of Air Power" held at the Library of Congress March 7, 1949. In addition, newspaper clippings about James Forrestal, including a May 23, 1949 article from the Evening Star chronicle his career and suicide of that year. An August 9, 1949 article from the Washington Daily News entitled "No Politics Behind B-36, Lovett Says" details the Senate investigation into the Wartime orders for the B-36 bomber. Two newspaper photographs of Prince Charles of England at age 8 months and one year as well as a December 3, 1949 obituary for the Playwright Phillip Barry are also included.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A maroon scrapbook (9.5" x 11.75" x 1.75") chronicling the Brown's family life during the period as well as national events upto the start of the Korean war. Numerous family photos and cards are included from family vacations. The birth of the Brown's third son, Robert Lovett Brown on January 26, 1951 at Columbia Hospital, Washington, D.C. is noted through his birth certificate, announcements, and telegrams. The Brown's first home in Fairfax County Virginia is pictured and a "Home Location Survey" for it are in the scrapbook. Also, a newspaper article about the sub-division, "Belle View", site of the Brown's home, is included. Brown's itinerary for his trip to Europe in August 1951 as an employee of the Economic Cooperation Committee (ECA) is included. Also contained in the scrapbook is an article on William Foster's appointment to Chief of ECA, articles on Robert A. Lovett's appointment to Deputy Defense Secretary in 1950, programs and a ticket from the 195l christening of the USS United States in Newport News, Virginia, a program cover from the Aviation Education Conference in 1950 to which Brown was a consultant, some of Brown's articles and writings from the period, and an invitation to the midpoint anniversary observance of the Marshall Plan on April 3, 1950. Finally, an article on Princess Dayan Djavidan, widow of Khedive Abbass Hilmi, former King of Egypt, and a Saturday Evening Post cover from January 7, 1950 picturing Congress in session are included. The last page of the book contains a newspaper photo of Robert A. Lovett as Defense Secretary, Senator Hoyt S. Vanberg as Air Force Chief and Thomas Finletter as Secretary of Air Force travelling to the White House for a meeting on the "Critical Situation in Korea."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A blue scrapbook (9.5" x 11.75" x 1.5") containing family photos of vacations and holidays as well as extensive material on Robert A. Lovett's succession of G. C. Marshall as Secretary of Defense in September 1951. Included in the book are a cover of a New York Times magazine from September 23, 1951 picturing Robert A. Lovett, articles on the subsequent reorganization of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, a newspaper article from Rio de Janerio, September 14, 1951, on Robert A. Lovett's appointment. Among the other items that commemorate Robert A Lovett's promotion include two black and white photographs of Robert A. Lovett being sworn in and standing near George C. Marshall, another black and white photograph from an interview picturing Robert A. Lovett and his wife, as well as an article about Robert A. Lovett in U. S. Air Services magazine in October 1951. There are several newspaper, colored clippings picturing Mrs. Lovett in various fashionable outfits as well as Brown's invitation to the White House on October 31, 1951. Newspaper photos from the visit of the then princess Elizabeth of England to Washington in October 1951 are included along with an obituary for King George Vi, her father, newspaper photos of his funeral and a full page color drawing of Elizabeth as Queen. Four 8 x 10 black and white photos of Churchill and Truman from 1952 as well as a photograph of a quest book with the signatures of Truman and Churchill are historically significant. An article on the Burgandy Farm School in Alexandria, Virginia describes educational ideas in vogue at the time. Finally, newspaper clippings detailing the firing of Attorney General McGrath by Truman are included.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A red scrapbook with cream-colored binding (9"x11 3"x1 3/8") containing memorabilia from the Truman administration and from the 1952 presidential election as well as family photographs. Seven newspaper clippings captioned "The Changing White House" present historical views of the President's home and together with 11 magazine photographs, some in color of the "White House Redecorated," a before and after picture of the remodeling done by President and Mrs. Truman is presented. Other items from the Truman era include an invitation to the Truman Farewell on May 14, 1952, a pamphlet entitled "Unity, Strength, Freedom: A report to the Nation" from Armed Forces Day, May 17, 1952, and a map of Bolling Air Force Base made for the Armed Forces Day celebration there. Items from the 1952 Presidential campaign include newspaper clippings of Eisenhower after retiring from the armed forces, an 8 x 10 photograph of Eisenhower and Secretary of State Dean Acheson, an 8 x 10 photograph of Eisenhower at his retirement ceremony, memorabilia from the July 1952 Republican Convention including two colored drawings of Mamie and Dwight Eisenhower, and memorabilia from the Democratic Convention including a color drawing of Adalia Stevenson and his wife as well as drawings of other Democratic presidential nominees. An article from the Houston Post September 24, 1952 gives the text of the speech of the Republican Vice-President nominee, Richard Nixon made in responding to allegations of dishonesty about donations to his campaign. Two newspaper photographs of Eisenhower are included, one during his December 1952 trip to Korea and one of him and his wife at the victory celebration after the 1952 election. Miscellaneous historical events chronicled by the scrapbook include the building of a UN headquarters (newspaper photographs and articles), Queen Elizabeth of England's First Parliament (newspaper photograph), and the wedding of Anne D. Goodrich to Prince in exile Edmond Poniatowski of Poland in May 1952 (newspaper article). Family souvenirs include a program from the "1952 Scouting Exposition" at the DC Armory in May 1952, two 8 x 10 photographs of an unidentified man, perhaps Robert A. Lovett, receiving a degree, articles on Robert A. Lovett, Articles on the Burgandy Farm School, vacation pictures, the Brown children's artwork and letters to their parents.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This red and cream-colored scrapbook (9" x 11 3/4" x 1 3/8") contains family photos, articles about the Brown children's schools and the birth certificate of Adele Quarterly? Brown born November 6, 1953. Of historical significance are newspaper clippings detailing the end of the Korean War, the April 1953 death of Queen Mary of England, and a series of five newspaper photographs entitled "It happened in 1953" depicting Ben Hogan winning the British Open Golf Tournament, Sir Edmund Hillary after climbing Mt. Everest, the Korean Truce, the 50th anniversary of the Wrights' flight at Kitty Hawk and the succession of Stalin by Malenkov as Soviet Premier. Also of interest are photographs from the 1953 inauguration as well as a program and ticket to the parade. The scrapbook includes a guest and contribution list from the "Eastern States Jefferson-Jackson Democrat Dinner" in February 1953, which gives David S. Brown's name as a guest. Underneath the guest list is the handwritten notation, "David was there - a guest if not a contributor. The publication of this list ended his government career a few months later (September 1953)." Two other items of interest are a March 1953 House and Garden pictorial featuring Robert A. Lovett's home and a colored newspaper photograph of Queen Frederika of Greece.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This red and cream scrapbook (9" x 11 3/4" x 1 3/8") contains many family Christmas cards and photographs as well as interesting newspaper clippings. Significant clippings include a large (2 8 x 10 sheets) magazine photograph of the House of Representatives two minutes after Puerto Rican terrorists shot at the assembly in 1954, newspaper drawings of the hydrogen bomb test explosions of the year, a newspaper photo of the four minute mile barrier being broken by a runner. Other interesting items are a program from the Jefferson-Jackson Democratic Dinner 1954 that lists Brown as a guest, clippings from Brown's PHD dissertation, several newspaper articles stating that George Washington University had named Brown as an Associate Professor of Public Administration, newspaper photographs of Hurricane Carol in September 1954, and Brown's invitation to a Mexican Embassy reception and to a Saudi Arabian Embassy reception. A large 8 x 10 newspaper photograph of Albert Schweitzer building a hospital with the help of a native man is also included.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This red and black scrapbook (13" x 15" x 3 3/8") contains some materials on George Washington University such as a newspaper photograph of a George Washington parking lot with a "Park it yourself" device, a newspaper article titled "GW Area Urban Renewal Ok'd", a program from George Washington University's Air Force Advanced Management Program, Convocation Exercises August 10, 1956 and 8 x 10 photographs of the same occasion, as well as clippings from a 1956 George Washington University publication titled "The University Faculty". Personal mementoes include 8 x10 photographs of Brown's PHD commencement at Syracuse University in June 1955 in addition to a complete 1955 issue of the Syracuse Daily Orange detailing the commencement and a program from the occasion. Family vacation photographs, articles by Brown and about Brown and his work with the Bakery and Confectioner Workers' Union, and a ticket to the July 10, 1956 All Star Game are also included. Of historical significance are a newspaper article on the polio vaccine, a newspaper picture of and article on the USS Forrestal, newspaper articles on Robert A. Lovett, newspaper articles on the August 1955 Summit as well as articles on President Eisenhower's heart attack and subsequent intestinal surgery. Also interesting are a January 1956 political pamphlet supporting the "Gray Plan" on school integration in Virginia and articles about that plan, a series of magazine clippings titled "Truman Memories", a color magazine photograph of Winston Churchill, one of Dr. Alexander Fleming who discovered penicillin, and one of Prince Rainier and Grace Kelly at their wedding. Two other items are newspaper articles on the demise of the cruise ship the Andrea Doria, and an invitation to Eisenhower's January 1957 Inaugural Ball.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A black and red scrapbook (11 1" x 14 1" x 2 1") contains many pictures, postcards, pamphlets and itinerary plans from the Browns' tour of Belgium, France, Holland and Italy. A newspaper article and personal memorabilia record Brown's stint as a visiting professor at the Royal Institute of Science and Technology in Glasgow, Scotland. Included also are an article on the retiring of George Washington University president Marvin, a clipping from the Daily Scottish Mail May 30, 1958 on the sentencing of mass murderer Manuel, a newspaper picture of an oil tanker on the Potomac river sent to avoid a shortage during a winter storm in Washington and numerous articles on Burgandy Farm School. A certificate for Brown from the Chemical Corps School at Fort McClellan Alabama in 1958, a program from the 1958 Campaign Conference for Democratic Women, and a program from the 1958 "Conference on Politics" held at Georgetown University are also contained in this scrapbook.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A black and red scrapbook (11" x 14 1" x 2 1") containing additional material (Photographs, tickets, postcards, etc.) from the Browns' European vacation, photographs of family and the children's camp, an obituary for Brown's father, and several playbills from the National Theater. Professional materials of Brown's include articles on the Baker's and Confectionery Workers' Union which employed Brown as a management advisor, as well as several 8 x 10 photographs of Brown giving lectures and at professional dinners, and a program from the Educational Buyers meeting held at George Washington University in October 1959 at which Brown was a speaker.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A brown scrapbook (10 1" x 13 3" x 1 1") contains material on George Washington University such as an article of George Washington University professor Dr. Burnice Jarman for Korea, photographs of Brown's coworkers at George Washington University, an article on A. M. Woodruff who was then Dean of the School of Government at George Washington University, an article on the "Behavioral Science Center" at George Washington University, as well as a December 1960 issue of George Washington University's AFM Gazette. Family memorabilia includes programs and photographs from the Brown children's school athletic events and class pictures, family vacation photographs and playbills from the Arena Stage. Professional material of Brown's includes various programs from management training seminars at which Brown spoke such as the Army Medical Specialist Corps Supervisors course and the IRS Management Institute, and an 8 x 10 photograph of Brown and a group at the "US Treasury Law Enforcement Officers Training School". Of historical interest are a magazine photograph of the SSBN-GW captioned "World's First Missile Subs", articles on Robert A. Lovett, newspaper clippings about the engagement of Britain's Princess Margaret, 8 x 10 photographs from the Democratic Leaders Training Conference of 1960, articles on John F. Kennedy's presidential victory and a small card printed "Thank you for your help" and signed by John F. Kennedy in ink to Brown.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A brown scrapbook (10 1/4" x 13 1/4" x 1 1") containing photographs of the Brown family's travel in Pakistan, a pamphlet in Indian on manners for Pakistani and Indian travelers, a clipping from the Civil and Military Gazette of Lahore, Pakistan on the Institute of Public administration at which Brown taught for 18 months as well as 8 x 10 photographs and programs from the opening of the school and a program from the first commencement of the school.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A brown scrapbook (10 1/4" x 13 1/4" x 1 1/4") containing photographs from the Brown family's travels in Spain, Italy, Greece and Pakistan as well as an issue of George Washington University's AFAM Gazette in April 1961 with an article "Brown leaves for Pakistan". Of historical interest are tickets to the January 1961 Inauguration and Ball of John F. Kennedy, newspaper clippings on the new cabinet and an Inaugural program and engraved invitation to the occasion.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A black and red scrapbook (13" x 15" x 3 1/2") containing memorabilia from the Brown family's time in Pakistan. Included are many photographs of Pakistan and India, itineraries, newspaper clippings from Lahore, Pakistan papers, a copy of the Pakistani National anthem, several issues of LAS Times (Lahore American School newspaper), and an invitation to a reception for the King and Queen of Pakistan. Numerous satirical and professional writings of Brown's are included. Historically interesting are magazine photographs of the Kennedy family, clippings on Mrs. Kennedy's trip to Pakistan, and clippings on the "Space Race", the first manned orbit of earth and the Indian elections of 1962.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A green scrapbook (12 1/4" x 15" x 1 1/2") containing additional photographs and memorabilia from the Brown family's stay in Pakistan. Included are a May 1962 issue of National Geographic, unpublished writings of Brown, several issues of Local News published by the US Information Service, as well as articles on the status of Pakistani women. Photographs from a Brown family trip to Thailand and of their departure from Pakistan on July 11, 1962 are also contained in the scrapbook along with several articles detailing Mrs. Kennedy's impression of Pakistan.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This maroon scrapbook (12" x 15" x 1 1/2") contains family photographs of the Brown family's travels in the Philippines, Japan and Yellowstone National Park. Also included are photographs of the graduation of Brown's oldest son, David S. Brown Jr., from Mercuberg Academy, Pennsylvania. The Brown children's artwork and photographs of their sporting events are also present. In addition to Christmas cards, letters and photographs, the scrapbook contains numerous articles on India and on Pakistan, a campus guide to George Washington University and a copy of the George Washington University Federalist from fall 1962 that contains an article by Brown.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A maroon scrapbook (12" x 15" x 1 1/2") containing family photographs, postcards of vacation photographs from Puerto Rico and St. Thomas, family cards and letters, playbills from local Washington theaters, newsletters from the Brown children's schools, and the cover of the program from the 23rd annual Ice Capades. Professional memorabilia of Brown's includes 8 x10 photographs of Brown giving lectures,an announcement of the election of Brown to the Vice Presidency of Leadership Resources Inc., program pages from the April "1963 National Conference on Public Administration", postcards and bulletin pages from Indiana University where Brown was a visiting professor and an article from Panorama June 1963 on Brown and a Pakistani student at George Washington University. Of historical interest are January 1963 articles on a record snowstorm in Maine, a magazine cover from May 1963 picturing the astronaut Cooper, magazine photographs of Pope John XXIII at his death on June 7, 1963, magazine photographs of Pope Paul VI, pages from the New York Times Magazine picturing those who had received the president's "freedom medal", and a Washington Post article of September 25, 1963 entitled "Senate Ratifies Test Ban Treaty." Also historically interesting are clippings, information pamphlets and other memorabilia from the solar eclipse of July 20, 1963, as well as an obituary for Paul H. Appleby, 2nd Dean of the Maxwell School of Syracuse University. Important material concerning the Washington, D.C. area includes a copy of the TWIG, a publication of the Jr. Auxillary of Alexandria Hospital as well as programs and photographs from the Auxillary's 30th annual ball. Newspaper clippings on an August flash flood in Alexandria in addition to magazine photos of the 1963 march on Washington also detail area history.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This green scrapbook (12" x 15" x 1 1/2") contains extensive material on the assassination of President John F. Kennedy. A magazine pictorial on John F. Kennedy and his family, magazine photographs of the assassination in Dallas as well as magazine photographs of the president's funeral and Lyndon Johnson's swearing in are included. Other historically significant material includes an invitation to the presentation of the president's "Medals of Freedom" on December 6, 1963 one of which was received by Robert A. Lovett. Articles on Roberat A. Lovett and his award as well as magazine photographs of Pope Paul IV in the Holy Land are also present. Family memorabilia includes flyers from the Brown children's schools as well as programs from the schools' sporting events, Christmas cards and photographs. Professional memorabilia of Brown's includes articles he authored and programs from various professional meetings. Materials about the Washington area includes a program from a performance at George Washington University's Lisner auditorium, clippings from George Washington University Newsletters, as well as an 8 x 10 photograph of the National Christmas tree. Another interesting item in the scrapbook is a collection of PTA letters from St. Stephen's school in Alexandria, Virginia authored by Brown on the topic of "Adolescence" and a speech on that subject given by Dr. Phillips of George Washington University.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A blue scrapbook (12" x 15" x 1 1/2") containing family photographs and the architect's blueprints for the Brown family's summer home in Maine. Professional material of Brown's contained in this scrapbook includes a bibliography of Brown's professional writings, newspaper clippings mentioning the work of Brown as well as various research papers of Brown's. Some of the material included in the scrapbook deals with George Washington University such as clippings from George Washington University's faculty newsletter, a newspaper article detailing the fact that President Eisenhower was to be awarded an honorary degree at George Washington University's commencement in 1964, clippings from the George Washington University magazine Federal Issue, and, in addition obituaries for George Washington University president T. H. Carroll. Of historical interest are baseball souvenir scorecards from 1964, a playbill from the Plymouth Theater, magazine pictures of General Douglas McArthur's funeral, a booklet entitled "Tribute to Eleanor Roosevelt with her photograph on its cover, and a magazine photograph of the Indian statesman Nehru's funeral. Also included are tickets and a program from the USGA 64th open championship golfing tournament, magazine photographs of the 1964 World's Fair, a June 1964 article entitled "Senate Stops Filibuster on Rights Bill" dealing with the stalling of a civil rights bill by some Congressmen as well as white House invitations to a reception given by Lady Bird Johnson. Three other historically interesting items include memorabilia from the 1964 Campaign Conference for Democratic Women, an April 30, 1964 press release titled "Remarks of the President to 1964 Campaign Conference", as well as a three dimensional color picture with the handwritten notation "1st 3-d color picture". The scrapbook also contains several brochures from Washington are landmarks such as the Shrine of the Immaculate Conception, Washington Cathedral, Franciscan Monastery, Harper's Ferry, John Brown Wax Museum, Antietam battlefield, Mount Vernon and Gadsby's Tavern.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A blue scrapbook (15" x 12" x 1.5") containing family photographs, Christmas and Valentine cards, wedding announcements of friends of the Browns, postcards to family members during business trips, several 'Peanuts' comic strips as well as memorabilia from the Brown Children's athletic events.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A black scrapbook contains photos, news paper clippings, and a System and Procedure Journal of May 1965. Moreover, it also contains Brown's and family photos at Long Island, Maine, Compobello Island, Blue Nose, Windsor, Canada, Wyo valley, wedding of John and Joan Sylvester at Lucerne Inn, football match of St. Stephan vs Georgetown, and St. Agnes school spring festival.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook contains different news paper clippings including articles by Mr. brown. Photos of Chris at 17 and his graduation, Hockey Day at St. Agnes, Trip to Florida, Christmas Day, fishing at Rochester with Bob Brown, Lyn in hospital and places like James town, Norfolk, Botanical Garden. Get Well cards to Lyn, Christmas cards to the Browns and copy of the 112th Cyracus University Commencement.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook contains photos of Mr. Brown's family, Adelle's Locust Valley visit, Visit to Anderson college at Rchobatu, Evie's childhood, Christmas, Mr. Brown's 25th Wedding Anniversary, his new cottage, with Senator Jackson, Kimbal store, and family home. Mr. Browns membership cards, a letter from Mrs. Lyndon B. Johnson, the former President's wife. The obituary of Evelyn Brown (1967) and death of Robert F. Kennedy (1968) is also included.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This green scrapbook contains photos of Dr. Brown's marriage to Anne Elizon Brown, including those at church, receptions. Photos from visits to Quebec, family photos at different places including Campobello Island, Lac du Flambeau, Maine, Thanksgiving and Adele at St. Timothy.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A reddish, brown scrapbook (14.75" x 12.25" x 1.5") in poor condition. It contains mostly pictures of DSB and family. Among the photographs included are pictures of family vacations, holidays, and other family events. In addition there are newspaper clippings on Charles de Gaulle's resignation as president of France, Eisenhower's death, and the lunar landing.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This scrapbook (14.25" x 12.125" x 1.5") has a bright red cover. In it are pictures of DSB at speaking engagements, of graduations (children), DSB's wedding anniversary, and of the family dog Ralph. There are also many personal letters between DSB and family and an invitation to testify in front of Congress.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This lime green scrapbook (14.25" x 12.125" x 1.5") holds a lot of invitations to events(daughter Adele's graduation and other professional events). There are also pictures of Adele's graduation as well as pictures from their European Vacation England, France, Yugoslavia, Austria) and from Christmas.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A marbled - brown scrapbook (16.00" x 14.00" x 1.5") with plenty of greeting cards from different holidays (Father's & Mother's day, Valentines day, birthday, Christmas, Easter, and anniversary). There are professional writings and descriptions of DSB. Finally there are clippings of J. Edger Hoover's and Truman's death.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A marbled - brown scrapbook (16.00" x 14.00" x 1.5") with several theater programs and personal letters. Pictures include those of birthdays, holidays, and a few special events (balls,etc). There are clippings of LBJ's and Picasso's death and of the Watergate scandal.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A dark green scrapbook (16.25" x 13.5" x 3") containing news clippings on local events, Watergate, the Energy Crisis, and the SR-71(a supersonic spy plane). There are pictures of the yearly retreat to Maine summer cottage, of special days (e.g. Christmas, Valentines day, etc.) and of the yearly vacation to Europe (this time to Portugal, Andorra, and France).

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook (16.25" x 13.50 x 1.75") has news clippings of the Watergate participants that were found guilty (i.e. Mitchell, Halteman, Maridian, Ehrlichman), of talks between Ford and British Prime Minister Wilson, Saigon's surrender to North Vietnam, and sporadic local events. There are also mementoes from a local vacation to Williamsburg, from Chris's wedding to Connie, from Adele's graduation from College, from the trip to Maine, and from the marriage of DSB jr. There are pictures of all these events as well.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook (16.50" x 13.50" x 2.50") contains several mementoes from the 200th anniversary of the United States including postcards and a special issue of Time magazine. There are pictures of birthdays, vacation in Virginia, DSB's trip to EL Salvador and Mexico, vacation to Ireland, marriage of Robert Brown and Christmas. Finally there are clippings of Carter and his campaign, an excavation led by Chris Brown, the death of Mao Tse Tung, and the Concord Supersonic Passenger Jet.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: In this brown scrapbook (16.25" x 13.50" x 2.50") there are pictures of the usual birthdays and events (Valentine's day, Mother's day, Christmas, and Trip to Maine). There are also clippings of Jimmy Carter's inauguration, death of Elvis, construction of Alaskan Pipeline, and the Egypt-Israel Peace Agreement.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This dark brown scrapbook (16.25" x 13.50" x 2") contains clippings of Hubert Humphrey's death, of a snowstorm in D.C., and Pope Paul VI's death. There are pictures of the snowstorm, family birthdays (including Anne's 37), vacation to Grand Canyon and Las Vegas and France, social events, public speaking events featuring DSB, and Christmas.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: In this dark brown scrapbook (16.25" x 13.50" x 2") there are several clippings of the Washington D.C. snowstorm, the Egypt-Israel peace Agreement, sports articles, obituaries of acquaintances, professional publications, trip to Quebec, the installment of Margaret Thatcher, and the takeover of US embassy in Teheran. The pictures include Rob and Anne's and DSB's birthday, trip to Harper's ferry, Valentines Day, trip to London and Scotland, and Christmas.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook (16.00" x 13.25" x 2.00") contains many pictures of DSB's trip to Massachusetts, California, Yosemite, Washington, Poland, Denmark, Norway, Holland, Belgium, Luxembourg, France, and Vienna. There are clippings of earthquakes, Mt. St. Helens eruption, GWU expansion, 1980 election and boycott of the Olympics. Additionally there are pictures of family get-togethers (birthday, visits, and Christmas).

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This brown scrapbook (16.25" x 13.50" 1.5") contains clippings of DSB's speech at NCSA, an article in the Washington Post, several professional articles, death of one of DSB's students, Reagan's inauguration, death of GW official, safari in Kenya, Tanzania, and Sudan (Postcards and maps of the area), attempted assassination of Reagan, first flight of space shuttle, Di and Charles's wedding, Sandra Day O'Connor's appointment, Sadat's assassination, and Poland's military takeover. There are a few pictures of mother's day, his safari, and Christmas.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This black scrapbook (14.50" x 11.25" x 2") with a broken spine contains pictures of new grandchildren (Kim), DSB's trip to Georgia and Maine, family birthdays, Valentines day, Mother's and Father's day, and Christmas. There are also clippings of an airplane crash, sports events, George Washington University's academic standing, the First edition of the Washington Times, Al Haig's resignation, and of DSB's book release.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This black scrapbook (14.50" x 11.25" x 2") contains more pictures of DSB's trip to Georgia, Rob's birthday, DSB shoveling snow, the European vacation (Iceland, Paris, Hungary, Italy, Czechoslovakia, and West Germany), and Christmas. There are clippings of the Redskin's Super Bowl victory, the snow storm in D.C., Nolan Ryan's new career strikeout record, the shooting down of the Korean 747, Grenada Invasion, the hostages in Lebanon and mementoes from the European vacation.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: A black scrapbook (14"x11.5"x2") containing family photographs, newspaper clippings and some articles written by Dr. Brown. Also contains clippings and photographs of Dr. Brown celebrating the 30th Anniversary of the programs in Public Administration at G.W.. Besides, the scrapbook contains a list of books Dr. Brown read from August 20, 1983 to August 19, 1984 (138 to be exact!)

odd.head: General note
odd.p: This scrapbook (14"x11"x2") contains a mixture of family pictures, newspaper clippings and articles written by Dr. Brown, ranging from 1981 to 1988. There is a tribute to Dr. Brown, honoring him as founder of the Public Administration Programs at G.W. and awarding him the Distinguished Service Award. Also, there are pictures of the Class of 1936 50th Alumni Reunion at the University of Maine (Dr. Brown's Alma Mater). It also contains clippings about the publication of his book: "Management's Hidden Enemy-and what can be done about it."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Contains family photographs, greeting cards, newspaper clippings and articles.
